      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Even the most sophisticated AI systems don't always get it right. Forecasting is incredibly powerful, but it's not perfect, and when a prediction misses the mark, the consequences can ripple through your entire operation surprisingly quickly. You might find that stock runs out when you least expect it, leaving customers waiting and your team scrambling. Or perhaps waste levels suddenly spike because the system didn't anticipate a shift in demand, and now you're dealing with spoilage or excess that nobody planned for. In either case, operations can slow down or even grind to a halt, and that's when the real costs start to add up. We're talking about lost sales, emergency orders, unhappy customers, and wasted resources. So in this lesson, we're going to look honestly at where AI forecasting can fall short, why it happens, and what you can do to protect your business when predictions don't quite match reality."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "Before we explore what AI can do, it helps to understand what poor forecasting actually costs a business. When you order too much stock, that extra inventory sits on the shelf tying up cash that could be doing something more useful elsewhere in the business. Order too little, and your customers leave empty-handed, often heading straight to a competitor. Then there is the issue of perishable goods. If products expire before they are sold, that is a direct financial loss with no way to recover it. And the problems do not stay contained. A bad forecast in one part of the supply chain can cause delays and disruption all the way down the line. What makes this particularly tricky is that none of these issues tend to announce themselves loudly. They quietly chip away at your profit margins over time. So the stakes here are very real, and that is exactly why getting forecasting right matters so much."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So we've established that forecasting matters, but what actually happens when it goes wrong? Well, the consequences fall on both sides. Order too much stock and you've got cash sitting on shelves, taking up valuable warehouse space, and if those products are perishable, you're looking at spoilage and waste on top of that. Order too little, and your shelves are empty, customers walk away disappointed, and if it keeps happening, they stop coming back altogether. That reputational damage is very real and very hard to recover from. Now, you might think a small forecasting error here and there isn't a big deal, but when you're managing hundreds or even thousands of product lines, those small errors multiply quickly and the financial impact adds up fast. This is exactly why getting forecasting right is so critical, and it's also why so many businesses are now turning to AI to help them do it better."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "So what actually happens when a forecast goes wrong? Well, the consequences tend to fall into two camps. Either you've ordered too little and suddenly find yourself with empty shelves, turning customers away who leave frustrated and quite possibly never come back. Or you've ordered too much, and now you're staring at surplus stock that's taking up space, tying up your cash, and in many cases, heading straight for the bin. Both situations are costly, and the damage adds up faster than most people expect. Wasted product means wasted money. Lost sales mean lost revenue. And when customers have a poor experience, you lose their trust as well. So poor forecasting isn't just a minor inconvenience, it genuinely eats into your profits and your reputation. This is exactly why getting inventory planning right matters so much, and it's the problem that AI is particularly well placed to help solve."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "So what actually happens when your forecasts are off? Well, it cuts both ways. If you overestimate demand, you end up with too much stock sitting on shelves, tying up cash you could be using elsewhere, and taking up storage space you might not have. And if that stock is perishable, you are looking at spoilage and write-offs on top of that. But underestimating is just as damaging. Run out of stock and you lose sales, disappoint customers, and risk them going elsewhere permanently. Either way, your relationships with suppliers start to suffer too, because inconsistent ordering makes you a difficult partner to work with. And here is the thing that catches a lot of teams off guard: these are not isolated mistakes. Across a large product range, even small forecasting errors stack up very quickly. The financial hit is significant, but the reputational damage, both internally and externally, can take much longer to recover from."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "So what actually happens when a forecast gets it wrong? Well, the consequences can ripple through a business very quickly. On one end, you might find that popular products simply run out, leaving customers empty-handed and frustrated. On the other end, you could end up with far too much stock sitting on shelves, taking up space and slowly losing value. And when products expire or go unsold, waste starts to climb. All of this puts real pressure on costs, because you are either scrambling to reorder urgently, often at a premium, or writing off stock that never sold. But perhaps the most damaging consequence is what happens to customer trust. If someone visits your store or website and finds the item they need is out of stock, they may simply go elsewhere, and they might not come back. So inaccurate forecasting is not just an operational headache, it genuinely affects your bottom line and your reputation."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So what actually happens when a forecast gets it wrong? Well, the consequences ripple out in several directions at once. On one hand, you might find yourself completely out of stock on a popular item, leaving customers empty-handed and frustrated. On the other hand, you could end up with far too much of something, with products piling up on shelves, taking up space, and slowly losing value. When perishable goods are involved, that surplus often ends up in the bin, and those waste costs can add up surprisingly quickly. And here is the thing about customers: once they experience a gap on the shelf or a product they needed simply is not there, their confidence in you starts to wobble. They may quietly start shopping elsewhere. All of this, the waste, the lost sales, the disappointed customers, feeds directly into your bottom line. Forecasting errors are not just operational headaches; they are genuinely expensive business problems."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let us bring together the core lessons from this session. First, AI is a powerful tool, but it is not infallible. Always have a contingency plan in place, because when predictions go wrong, the effects can spread quickly across your entire supply chain. That is why regular monitoring matters so much. Do not just set your AI system running and walk away. Check in on it consistently. And when something does go wrong, take the time to understand why, not just fix the immediate issue. You will often find that the root cause is surprisingly simple, like poor quality data at the input stage. Small data problems can cause surprisingly large disruptions. Finally, here is a practical challenge for you this week. Pick just one process in your operation where AI is currently supporting decisions, and take a closer look at how accurate it actually is. That single step can teach you an enormous amount."
        }
      ]
    }
